{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3e25d39e-7b62-4f00-b0e5-3974be5d61eb","content":"**.NET MAUI (since .NET 8) bundles its own Microsoft OpenJDK 17** and the Android build targets use it automatically. When you set `JAVA_HOME` to a different distribution (Adoptium Temurin), it overrides the bundled JDK and can cause build failures due to subtle distribution differences.\n\n**Fix — choose one:**\n\n1. **Unset `JAVA_HOME`** so the build uses the bundled JDK:\n   ```bash\n   unset JAVA_HOME\n   # Then rebuild\n   dotnet build -t:Rebuild\n   ```\n   Remove or comment out any `export JAVA_HOME=...` line in your `~/.zshrc` / `~/.bash_profile`.\n\n2. **Or point it to the bundled Microsoft OpenJDK:**\n   ```bash\n   export JAVA_HOME=\"/usr/local/share/dotnet/packs/Microsoft.Android.Sdk.Darwin/*/tools/jdk\"\n   ```\n   (The exact path varies by SDK version — check with `dotnet workload list` and look under the Android SDK pack directory.)\n\n3. **Or set it per-project** in your `.csproj`:\n   ```xml\n   <PropertyGroup>\n     <JavaSdkDirectory>$(DOTNET_DIR)/packs/Microsoft.Android.Sdk.Darwin/.../tools/jdk</JavaSdkDirectory>\n   </PropertyGroup>\n   ```\n\n**Option 1 (unsetting `JAVA_HOME`) is the simplest and recommended approach.** The .NET Android workload knows where its bundled JDK lives and will find it automatically.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"80880a8e-e055-418f-be9f-125505006bd5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI Android build failure related to Java. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed. Let me think about what the common issue is here.\n\nThis is a well-known issue: .NET MAUI / Xamarin Android builds require a specific JDK. Starting with .NET 8, the Android SDK build tools require JDK 17, but there's a specific issue with certain JDK distributions or versions.\n\nActually, the most common issue with .NET MAUI Android builds and Java is:\n\n1. **JDK version compatibility**: .NET 8+ MAUI requires JDK 17. The user has JDK 17, so that's fine.\n\n\n2. **The Microsoft OpenJDK requirement**: .NET MAUI on Android specifically expects the **Microsoft OpenJDK** distribution. While other JDK 17 distributions like Adoptium Temurin may work, there can be compatibility issues with certain distributions.\n\nThe real problem is likely that .NET Android ships with its own JDK and there's a conflict with the separately installed Temurin distribution, or the build system is encountering a `java.lang.UnsupportedClassVersionError` due to version mismatches.\n\nWith .NET 8+, the Android workload bundles Microsoft OpenJDK 17 and uses it automatically through the build system, but if `JAVA_HOME` is set to a different JDK distribution, it can override this and cause the build to pick up the wrong version. On macOS specifically, Adoptium Temurin installs to a path that might not be properly recognized by the .NET build system. The real issue is that .NET MAUI's build system prefers its bundled Microsoft OpenJDK 17, but an incompatible `JAVA_HOME` environment variable can override that and cause failures. The solution is straightforward: either unset `JAVA_HOME` entirely to let the bundled JDK take over, or explicitly point it to Microsoft's OpenJDK 17. This is a well-known configuration problem with .NET MAUI on macOS, so I can give a direct answer without needing to dig deeper.","outputTokens":1309},"id":"0d6be670-423b-4467-96ed-a4628c5ce8bb","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:47:35.030Z","parentId":"7ec1cf7c-93e1-43cc-b140-0f5cc4de3d95"}
